WEBVTT

00:02.002 --> 00:04.586
(Wil Willis voice-over)
Since the dawn
of human civilization,

00:04.630 --> 00:06.422
mankind has made weapons.

00:06.465 --> 00:08.340
[fire whooshes]
- Whoa!

00:08.384 --> 00:11.552
(Wil)
Bladesmiths have honed
and perfected their craft

00:11.595 --> 00:12.845
over thousands of years.

00:12.888 --> 00:14.221
(man)
Oh, yeah!

00:14.265 --> 00:16.015
(Wil)
And now,
for the first time ever,

00:16.058 --> 00:17.891
these men will go head-to-head

00:17.935 --> 00:19.727
and put their skills
to the ultimate test.

00:19.770 --> 00:21.437
Welcome to the forge.

00:21.480 --> 00:24.356
(Wil voice-over)
It starts with a lump
of raw steel

00:24.400 --> 00:25.733
and a ticking clock,

00:25.776 --> 00:27.484
and by the end of three rounds,

00:27.528 --> 00:30.195
the bladesmiths must deliver
handmade weapons

00:30.239 --> 00:31.530
that are works of art

00:31.574 --> 00:34.408
as well as deadly instruments
of war.

00:34.452 --> 00:37.661
These weapons must survive
explosive tests

00:37.705 --> 00:41.040
as well as the scrutiny
of an expert panel judges.

00:41.083 --> 00:45.210
In the end, only one bladesmith
will take home $10,000

00:45.254 --> 00:48.088
and be crowned
a<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

00:48.132 --> 00:51.091
[dramatic music]

00:51.135 --> 00:53.594
♪ ♪

00:58.934 --> 01:00.601
(James)
I'm James Hughes.

01:00.644 --> 01:03.729
I got into making knives
in 2000.

01:03.773 --> 01:06.231
It's the pride of being able to
make something with your hands,

01:06.275 --> 01:08.817
and make a useful piece of art.

01:08.861 --> 01:09.777
(Jonathan)
I'm Jonathan Porter,

01:09.820 --> 01:11.695
and I'm a farrier--

01:11.739 --> 01:14.073
the fancy word
for a horseshoer--

01:14.116 --> 01:17.409
as well as
a full-time bladesmith.

01:17.453 --> 01:18.911
(Ryu)
My name is Ryu Lim.

01:18.954 --> 01:20.913
I was born and raised
in the Philippines.

01:20.956 --> 01:22.122
I'm an ironworker,

01:22.166 --> 01:24.083
and I make blades for a living.

01:24.126 --> 01:25.584
(Phil)
My name is Phil Evans.

01:25.628 --> 01:28.295
I've been making knives
for almost 20 years.

01:28.339 --> 01:30.881
I made my first knife in 1995.

01:30.925 --> 01:34.551
I ground it out of a file and
put a deer antler handle on it.

01:34.595 --> 01:37.054
Gentlemen,
welcome to the forge.

01:37.098 --> 01:39.431
Ahead of you
are three challenges

01:39.475 --> 01:42.101
designed to test your skill.

01:42.144 --> 01:44.603
Each round is against the clock

01:44.647 --> 01:47.189
and of course,
against each other.

01:47.233 --> 01:48.774
After each round,

01:48.818 --> 01:50.776
our panel of judges
will scrutinize your work.

01:50.820 --> 01:53.987
They decide who stays,
and who goes.

01:54.031 --> 01:56.073
It's time to meet our judges.

01:56.117 --> 01:59.451
Solo weapons making export,
J. Neilson.

01:59.495 --> 02:02.788
Rare weapons recreation
specialist, David Baker.

02:02.832 --> 02:04.873
And finally,
edged weapons specialist

02:04.917 --> 02:09.169
and martial artist,
Doug Marcaida.

02:09.213 --> 02:12.881
In front of you,
on your anvils, is a cloth.

02:12.925 --> 02:15.843
Go ahead and lift that up.

02:15.886 --> 02:18.470
That is a train spring

02:18.514 --> 02:20.639
made of high-carbon steel.

02:20.683 --> 02:23.851
Your challenge
is to forge that spring

02:23.894 --> 02:25.853
into a weapon
of your own design

02:25.896 --> 02:28.355
but it should be
in your signature style.

02:28.399 --> 02:29.731
The length of the blade,

02:29.775 --> 02:31.150
not including the tang,

02:31.193 --> 02:35.362
must be between
12 and 16 inches.

02:35.406 --> 02:37.322
And just to spice things up
a little bit,

02:37.366 --> 02:40.826
that blade that you must create
must also have a fuller

02:40.870 --> 02:43.328
that runs over half the length
of the blade.

02:43.372 --> 02:44.830
(Phil)
I'm concerned 'cause

02:44.874 --> 02:46.206
I've never put a fuller
in a knife before.

02:46.250 --> 02:47.833
It's gonna be kind of tricky.

02:47.877 --> 02:49.168
(Wil)
You will have ten minutes

02:49.211 --> 02:50.711
to work on your design.

02:50.754 --> 02:53.547
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

02:53.591 --> 02:55.424
After your time is up,

02:55.467 --> 02:57.676
one of you will have
to surrender your weapon

02:57.720 --> 02:59.469
and go home.

02:59.513 --> 03:00.888
Good luck, bladesmiths.

03:00.931 --> 03:03.473
Your ten-minute design window
begins...

03:03.517 --> 03:05.017
Now.

03:05.060 --> 03:08.020
[heavy rock music]

03:08.063 --> 03:10.189
♪ ♪

03:10.232 --> 03:12.858
(Ryu)
My specialty is hunting knives

03:12.902 --> 03:14.359
and fighting knives.

03:14.403 --> 03:17.237
I want to mix those two together
into one blade,

03:17.281 --> 03:18.530
and I want it to work.

03:18.574 --> 03:20.199
In the Philippines,

03:20.242 --> 03:23.118
I forged my first sword
when I was ten years old.

03:23.162 --> 03:26.038
I felt the hot iron
move in my hand,

03:26.081 --> 03:27.873
being formed by the hammer
to my will,

03:27.917 --> 03:30.542
and I felt very powerful.

03:30.586 --> 03:31.585
I loved that sword.

03:31.629 --> 03:34.129
I slept next to it every night.

03:34.173 --> 03:35.756
♪ ♪

03:35.799 --> 03:37.257
(James)
My knife's gonna be

03:37.301 --> 03:39.426
a large Bowie-style knife.

03:39.470 --> 03:43.430
My specialty knife
is a hunting/utility knife.

03:43.474 --> 03:45.098
That is a big, big blade.

03:45.142 --> 03:46.725
Being a proud Texan,

03:46.769 --> 03:48.560
I make a knife
that I can be proud of--

03:48.604 --> 03:52.564
that anybody who carries one
of my knives can be proud of.

03:52.608 --> 03:56.735
I'm making a broken back
or Viking-style seax.

03:56.779 --> 03:58.445
Divided by...

03:58.489 --> 04:00.822
I used to work at a horse show,

04:00.866 --> 04:03.367
and they're typically pretty
boring for the farrier.

04:03.410 --> 04:05.577
You're just waiting
on somebody's shoe to fall off.

04:05.621 --> 04:08.956
So I decided at that point
I was going to make some knives,

04:08.999 --> 04:11.083
and after the first couple
that I made,

04:11.126 --> 04:12.751
that's pretty much
what I did at horse shows.

04:12.795 --> 04:14.795
♪ ♪

04:14.838 --> 04:16.255
(Phil)
My design is for a Bowie knife

04:16.298 --> 04:17.756
with a hidden tang.

04:17.800 --> 04:20.968
My specialty in knife making
is a hunting knife

04:21.011 --> 04:23.470
or skinning knife, so I wanted
to stick with what I knew.

04:23.514 --> 04:25.430
My dad was blind.

04:25.474 --> 04:27.683
Almost every knife
that I made, I showed him.

04:27.726 --> 04:29.309
He couldn't see it,
but he would feel it.

04:29.353 --> 04:32.312
He could feel imperfections
that I couldn't see,

04:32.356 --> 04:33.981
which made me
a better knife maker.

04:34.024 --> 04:35.315
(Wil)
Gentlemen,

04:35.359 --> 04:38.485
your design window
is now closed.

04:38.529 --> 04:41.738
Your three-hour
forging time begins now.

04:41.782 --> 04:43.323
♪ ♪

04:43.367 --> 04:44.366
Here we go.

04:44.410 --> 04:48.912
♪ ♪

04:48.956 --> 04:49.955
Threw 'em a little bit
of a loop

04:49.999 --> 04:51.039
on the size of that material.

04:51.083 --> 04:52.624
(J.)
Yeah.

04:52.668 --> 04:55.043
They're just trying to get
their steel in the fire.

04:55.087 --> 04:58.588
♪ ♪

04:58.632 --> 05:00.674
(J.)
Phil got through part of it.

05:00.718 --> 05:02.634
He took a piece off.

05:02.678 --> 05:03.802
(Dave)
He just took enough off--

05:03.846 --> 05:04.803
(J.)
He took enough off

05:04.847 --> 05:05.846
to get it fit in there.

05:05.889 --> 05:07.306
- That was a good move.
- Yeah.

05:07.349 --> 05:08.807
(J.)
All right,

05:08.851 --> 05:10.058
so we're gonna
have number two in the fire.

05:10.102 --> 05:11.268
Looks like James
will be in the fire.

05:11.312 --> 05:13.603
Heat up,
heat up, heat up.

05:13.647 --> 05:14.938
(Jonathan)
Come on baby, get hot.

05:14.982 --> 05:16.356
Come on, come on,
come on, come on.

05:16.400 --> 05:18.567
Hate waiting on fire!

05:18.610 --> 05:22.195
- There you go. Here we go.
- There you go.

05:22.239 --> 05:23.488
- Oh, my goodness.
- That's all right.

05:23.532 --> 05:26.158
That's a lot
to hold onto there.

05:26.201 --> 05:27.743
(Phil)
I'm struggling with the spring.

05:27.786 --> 05:29.161
I dropped it.

05:29.204 --> 05:31.830
I couldn't get the tongs
to fit right.

05:31.874 --> 05:33.999
That metal is really
fighting Phil.

05:34.043 --> 05:35.375
(Phil)
I really don't know

05:35.419 --> 05:36.543
how I'm gonna get
that spring uncoiled

05:36.587 --> 05:38.337
and get it done in three hours.

05:38.380 --> 05:39.338
(J.)
He's getting there, though.

05:39.381 --> 05:40.756
He's getting there.

05:40.799 --> 05:42.007
- This is quite a challenge.
- Oh, yeah.

05:42.051 --> 05:43.008
(Doug)
Quite a challenge.

05:43.052 --> 05:44.551
Half an hour gone.

05:44.595 --> 05:46.511
You have two and a half hours
remaining.

05:46.555 --> 05:48.388
Yay!

05:48.432 --> 05:49.890
(Ryu)
All these other guys

05:49.933 --> 05:51.516
got their springs in the forge.

05:51.560 --> 05:53.310
I'm falling way behind.

05:53.354 --> 05:55.103
(J.)
So Ryu's finally got a piece

05:55.147 --> 05:57.022
that he wants to work with,

05:57.066 --> 05:59.191
and he's got his metal
in the forge.

05:59.234 --> 06:01.360
I can make weapons
out of anything.

06:01.403 --> 06:02.569
Literally anything

06:02.613 --> 06:04.696
by myself with no assistance,

06:04.740 --> 06:07.074
with no help from machines.

06:07.117 --> 06:08.700
I want to do everything by hand,

06:08.744 --> 06:11.328
and I want to show people
how I make my blades.

06:11.372 --> 06:12.788
♪ ♪

06:12.831 --> 06:14.456
He's beating on
cold steel there.

06:14.500 --> 06:16.708
He's got to get that
a lot hotter.

06:16.752 --> 06:18.377
I believe it's more personal.

06:18.420 --> 06:20.712
You build a relationship
with that blade,

06:20.756 --> 06:22.005
and you give it life.

06:22.049 --> 06:23.590
You give it soul.

06:23.634 --> 06:24.716
(Doug)
Everything that he does

06:24.760 --> 06:25.717
is in a traditional technique.

06:25.761 --> 06:26.718
(J.)
Wow.

06:26.762 --> 06:27.719
(Doug)
And usually,

06:27.763 --> 06:28.720
they can get away with that,

06:28.764 --> 06:30.597
but with a time element here--

06:30.641 --> 06:32.933
you know, using
these other machines does help.

06:32.976 --> 06:34.559
(J.)
He might have to learn
how to adapt

06:34.603 --> 06:38.063
and use some of these tools.

06:38.107 --> 06:39.064
(Jonathan)
Come on, come on, come on,

06:39.108 --> 06:40.565
come on!

06:40.609 --> 06:42.150
(Wil)
So right now, it's just a race

06:42.194 --> 06:44.361
to see who can uncoil
this the fastest, at this point.

06:44.405 --> 06:45.779
(J.)
And James is the first one

06:45.823 --> 06:47.072
on the press.

06:47.116 --> 06:48.740
(James)
I consider myself an artist,

06:48.784 --> 06:50.617
because it's like
any other type of art.

06:50.661 --> 06:52.244
You know, you paint a painting.

06:52.287 --> 06:53.745
You take raw materials,
and you paint a painting.

06:53.789 --> 06:55.080
We do the same thing.

06:55.124 --> 06:57.791
We take raw materials
and we make art.

06:57.835 --> 07:04.923
♪ ♪

07:04.967 --> 07:07.259
(J.)
It looks like Jonathan
is getting the swing of things.

07:07.302 --> 07:08.427
(Jonathan)
I have this ability

07:08.470 --> 07:09.928
to look at a piece of steel

07:09.972 --> 07:11.513
and just see the atoms.

07:11.557 --> 07:14.266
It's just material
in front of me,

07:14.309 --> 07:15.517
and it's free.

07:15.561 --> 07:17.227
It can be moved
wherever you want,

07:17.271 --> 07:20.355
and we use the heat
as the mode of transportation.

07:20.399 --> 07:21.940
[groans loudly]

07:21.984 --> 07:26.278
I really enjoy
the process of breaking it down

07:26.321 --> 07:27.779
and putting it
back together again.

07:27.823 --> 07:29.906
I'm having fun, man.
I'm having fun.

07:29.950 --> 07:32.576
♪ ♪

07:32.619 --> 07:33.660
Now, Phil's over there,

07:33.704 --> 07:35.954
and he's just working his edge.

07:35.998 --> 07:38.331
Throwing it nice and easy.

07:38.375 --> 07:39.958
(Phil)
When I finally got it
straightened out,

07:40.002 --> 07:41.793
that's when I realize
I'm getting somewhere,

07:41.837 --> 07:43.503
instead of spinning my wheels.

07:45.674 --> 07:48.467
(J.)
Ryu's almost got it uncoiled.

07:48.510 --> 07:50.635
Jeez, he's just wasting
time right now,

07:50.679 --> 07:51.636
fighting with that coil.

07:51.680 --> 07:52.971
I know.

07:53.015 --> 07:54.306
(Ryu)
The only way I'm gonna catch up

07:54.349 --> 07:56.057
is if I uncoil this,

07:56.101 --> 07:58.435
and I actually
start working on it.

07:58.479 --> 08:00.479
(J.)
There you go. Just flip it.

08:00.522 --> 08:02.314
- There you go.
- There we go. Yeah.

08:02.357 --> 08:03.857
That's what we want to see.

08:03.901 --> 08:05.484
(J.)
There you go.

08:05.527 --> 08:07.819
That's a beautiful use
of the hardy hole.

08:07.863 --> 08:09.362
I want to see
what he can do--

08:09.406 --> 08:10.322
He's close enough
to put it in the press,

08:10.365 --> 08:11.448
or in the hammer--

08:11.492 --> 08:12.532
(Dave)
But again,

08:12.576 --> 08:16.203
that's not what
he works with.

08:16.246 --> 08:17.496
(Ryu)
All of a sudden,

08:17.539 --> 08:20.332
I felt like
I was gonna pass out.

08:20.375 --> 08:22.542
It's about 100 degrees in here.

08:22.586 --> 08:24.211
(Ryu)
I have to leave.

08:24.254 --> 08:26.546
I didn't want it to happen
in front of everybody.

08:26.590 --> 08:28.882
- Oh, what is he thinking?
- What did he just do?

08:28.926 --> 08:30.175
(Ryu)
This is it.

08:30.219 --> 08:32.219
I'm done.

08:32.262 --> 08:33.637
This is a disaster.

08:35.057 --> 08:37.974
[heavy rock chord]

08:41.396 --> 08:44.231
[heavy rock chord]

08:44.274 --> 08:45.690
(Ryu)
These forges

08:45.734 --> 08:48.777
goes for more than
2,000 degrees.

08:48.820 --> 08:50.237
And it's hot.

08:50.280 --> 08:51.780
I needed to walk away.

08:51.823 --> 08:53.114
I felt like I was gonna
pass out.

08:53.158 --> 08:54.866
I had to leave.

08:54.910 --> 08:56.660
I didn't want it to happen
in front of everybody.

08:56.703 --> 08:59.746
So he's just going
to the bathroom, I hope.

08:59.790 --> 09:01.540
(Doug)
Wow.

09:01.583 --> 09:03.708
I mean, he's got a lot of time
he's got to make up.

09:03.752 --> 09:06.711
[hammers pounding]

09:09.466 --> 09:10.382
(Ryu)
I'm laying down.

09:10.425 --> 09:11.841
In the background,

09:11.885 --> 09:14.052
I could hear
all these hammers pounding.

09:14.096 --> 09:15.470
I need to be out there, man.

09:15.514 --> 09:16.471
I need to go back out there.

09:16.515 --> 09:17.556
I'm losing time.

09:17.599 --> 09:19.891
♪ ♪

09:19.935 --> 09:21.476
When I walked back in,

09:21.520 --> 09:24.271
I felt like a gladiator
walking back into the arena.

09:24.314 --> 09:25.730
Get your head in it,
man.

09:25.774 --> 09:27.482
I've never used
these power tools before,

09:27.526 --> 09:29.901
like the power hammer
and the hydraulic press.

09:29.945 --> 09:32.070
But I was running out of time,

09:32.114 --> 09:33.321
and I needed to catch up.

09:33.365 --> 09:34.948
♪ ♪

09:34.992 --> 09:36.992
There we go.
That's what I want to see.

09:37.035 --> 09:39.077
♪ ♪

09:39.121 --> 09:41.705
Gentlemen,
you have 90 minutes remaining.

09:41.748 --> 09:44.249
♪ ♪

09:44.293 --> 09:47.460
(J.)
Phil's nailing
that spring fuller.

09:47.504 --> 09:49.129
(Phil)
I'm concerned about the fuller

09:49.172 --> 09:52.424
because I've never
put a fuller in a knife before.

09:52.467 --> 09:54.092
And I know if I go too deep
on this fuller,

09:54.136 --> 09:55.427
I may have to start a new blade

09:55.470 --> 09:57.429
or it could just be over for me.

09:57.472 --> 09:59.431
(J.)
One little slip with that press,

09:59.474 --> 10:01.099
and you could squeeze down
too thin,

10:01.143 --> 10:02.601
and it'll just blow out
the center.

10:02.644 --> 10:05.645
- Oh, wow.
- You got to be very careful.

10:05.689 --> 10:07.731
♪ ♪

10:07.774 --> 10:08.690
Oh.

10:10.152 --> 10:12.360
(Wil)
Oh, no.

10:12.404 --> 10:13.486
(J.)
That's what I was worried about.

10:13.530 --> 10:15.280
He's got it worked out so thin,

10:15.324 --> 10:17.032
it's not just gonna squeeze
down,

10:17.075 --> 10:18.033
'cause there's nothing
supporting the sides.

10:18.076 --> 10:19.284
(Wil)
Right.

10:19.328 --> 10:20.660
(J.)
He just needs to flatten it out

10:20.704 --> 10:21.995
and move on.

10:22.039 --> 10:25.332
♪ ♪

10:25.375 --> 10:27.792
(J.)
James is spending a lot of time
working that steel,

10:27.836 --> 10:29.961
and he's refined his tip
a couple times.

10:30.005 --> 10:31.004
Needs to deal with it
on the grinder.

10:31.048 --> 10:33.590
Stop stressing your metal.

10:33.634 --> 10:35.967
Every horseshoe
has a fuller.

10:36.011 --> 10:37.802
(Jonathan)
I can do this.

10:37.846 --> 10:40.639
I'm so concerned about hitting
that fuller in a straight line,

10:40.682 --> 10:43.975
I just let the blade
cool too quickly.

10:44.019 --> 10:46.061
And just forged cold steel.

10:46.104 --> 10:47.479
(J.)
I'm just cringing every time

10:47.522 --> 10:50.023
he's hitting that cold steel.

10:50.067 --> 10:52.150
Oh, my God!
[laughing]

10:52.194 --> 10:54.819
- What happened?
- Just broke my blade.

10:54.863 --> 10:56.363
(Jonathan)
Oh!

10:56.406 --> 10:57.989
- All that work.
- How did that happen?

10:58.033 --> 11:01.326
To say that my heart sank
is an understatement.

11:01.370 --> 11:04.996
Well,
where's my spring steel at?

11:05.040 --> 11:07.165
Back to square one.

11:07.209 --> 11:09.000
(Doug)
Don't give up. There you go.

11:09.044 --> 11:11.336
I went back and grabbed some
more steel from that spring.

11:11.380 --> 11:12.712
(James)
Bring it home, baby.

11:12.756 --> 11:14.214
(Jonathan)
So much for the plan!

11:14.257 --> 11:16.049
So much for the plan,
right?

11:16.093 --> 11:19.052
I can do a lot in 45 minutes.

11:19.096 --> 11:21.888
I know I'm gonna have
a lot of work to do,

11:21.932 --> 11:24.349
but as long as I can
turn something in

11:24.393 --> 11:27.310
that's better
than the other guys' stuff,

11:27.354 --> 11:29.854
I'll have a better chance
to get to the second round.

11:29.898 --> 11:31.189
♪ ♪

11:31.233 --> 11:32.732
(J.)
Hey, we got a grinder going.

11:32.776 --> 11:35.318
James is on the grinder.

11:35.362 --> 11:36.695
(James)
As I'm grinding,

11:36.738 --> 11:38.279
my eye catches
a little dark line.

11:38.323 --> 11:40.031
[bleep] damn it.

11:40.075 --> 11:41.866
You know right away
it's a crack.

11:41.910 --> 11:44.786
Oh, man,
I wanted to scream so loud.

11:44.830 --> 11:46.871
[metal shatters]

11:46.915 --> 11:49.207
That sucker broke like glass.

11:49.251 --> 11:50.959
(J.)
Oh, my goodness.

11:51.002 --> 11:53.211
(J.)
This is heartbreaking.

11:53.255 --> 11:55.255
It's almost impossible
to come back from.

11:55.298 --> 11:57.674
(James)
I guess it shows weakness
if you quit,

11:57.718 --> 11:58.883
but hey.

11:58.927 --> 12:00.218
No way.
I'm gonna do this.

12:00.262 --> 12:03.596
♪ ♪

12:03.640 --> 12:05.056
(Wil)
I mean, these guys do know

12:05.100 --> 12:06.766
that they have to quench
these things, correct?

12:06.810 --> 12:07.767
I would hope so.

12:07.811 --> 12:09.477
We said a finished blade.

12:09.521 --> 12:11.771
It's not finished
if it's not heat treated.

12:11.815 --> 12:13.732
(Wil)
So does anybody have a weapon

12:13.775 --> 12:15.191
that would pass round one?

12:15.235 --> 12:16.192
Nope.

12:16.236 --> 12:18.570
♪ ♪

12:18.613 --> 12:19.738
(Wil)
Gentlemen,

12:19.781 --> 12:21.740
you got less than seven minutes.

12:21.783 --> 12:25.410
I want a fully heat treated,
functional blade.

12:25.454 --> 12:26.828
(J.)
Come on, Phil.

12:26.872 --> 12:28.121
Put it in the oil,
you're the closest one.

12:28.165 --> 12:29.372
Ryu, get it in the oil.
Come on.

12:29.416 --> 12:30.415
(Wil)
These guys have forgotten

12:30.459 --> 12:31.458
they have to heat treat.

12:31.501 --> 12:32.751
They're just making profiles.

12:32.794 --> 12:34.294
(J.)
I want to see a finished blade.

12:34.337 --> 12:36.045
If it's long enough,
it's got a fuller,

12:36.089 --> 12:38.590
and it's hardened,
I'll be happy.

12:38.633 --> 12:39.549
(J.)
Oil! We have a quench.

12:39.593 --> 12:40.759
We have a quench.

12:40.802 --> 12:42.010
- We have a quench.
- Finally!

12:42.053 --> 12:43.803
(Wil)
So we have one contestant

12:43.847 --> 12:46.139
with a fully heat-treated blade
that is eligible for judging.

12:46.183 --> 12:48.266
And another one who can.

12:48.310 --> 12:50.643
(J.)
He could have done it
ten minutes ago.

12:50.687 --> 12:52.896
(Ryu)
Everybody is looking at me
like I'm crazy.

12:52.939 --> 12:55.648
But I know what I'm doing.

12:55.692 --> 12:56.649
(Wil)
Gentlemen,

12:56.693 --> 12:58.943
you have two minutes remaining.

12:58.987 --> 13:01.362
♪ ♪

13:01.406 --> 13:03.698
Okay,
so Jonathan's in the oil.

13:03.742 --> 13:05.950
(J.)
Thank goodness.

13:05.994 --> 13:07.869
One minute.
One minute.

13:07.913 --> 13:10.455
- Seriously? With a minute?
- What? Really?

13:10.499 --> 13:11.831
(J.)
Less than a minute.

13:11.875 --> 13:13.750
Well, I'll take anything
at this point.

13:13.794 --> 13:15.293
(Wil)
Then seconds.

13:15.337 --> 13:17.128
Nine, eight,

13:17.172 --> 13:18.671
seven, six,

13:18.715 --> 13:21.424
five, four, three...

13:21.468 --> 13:23.802
- Whoa!
- Two, one.

13:23.845 --> 13:24.886
(Wil)
Gentlemen,

13:24.930 --> 13:26.471
stop what you're doing.

13:26.515 --> 13:27.972
(Jonathan)
I'm really embarrassed

13:28.016 --> 13:29.808
that I broke that blade,

13:29.851 --> 13:34.020
but I've cranked out a whole
second knife in 45 minutes.

13:34.064 --> 13:35.355
(James)
You know, all I had

13:35.398 --> 13:36.397
was a half-smashed
piece of steel there

13:36.441 --> 13:38.024
that's incomplete.

13:38.068 --> 13:42.237
You know, I just couldn't
fulfill the challenge.

13:42.280 --> 13:45.490
Gentlemen, your challenge
was to forge a blade

13:45.534 --> 13:48.827
from a train spring
made of high-carbon steel

13:48.870 --> 13:51.246
that was between
12 and 16 inches.

13:51.289 --> 13:53.873
Additionally,
your blade must include a fuller

13:53.917 --> 13:57.252
that runs at least
half the length of the blade.

13:57.295 --> 13:59.838
Phil, please present
your weapon.

13:59.881 --> 14:04.926
♪ ♪

14:04.970 --> 14:07.512
You had a little bit of trouble
during the heat treat.

14:07.556 --> 14:10.723
You got a warp
in this blade.

14:10.767 --> 14:11.933
(Dave)
I like the shape to your knife.

14:11.977 --> 14:14.727
I like the drop
to the handle.

14:14.771 --> 14:17.105
In a chopper, that really adds
a lot to it.

14:17.148 --> 14:19.107
- Congratulations.
- Thank you very much.

14:19.150 --> 14:22.485
Ryu, you may present your weapon
to the judges.

14:22.529 --> 14:26.030
♪ ♪

14:26.074 --> 14:27.699
(J.)
Ryu, the overall shape
is really nice.

14:27.742 --> 14:29.534
Thank you, sir.

14:29.578 --> 14:31.870
(J.)
I mean, it's gonna be
a nice chopping blade.

14:31.913 --> 14:35.915
Now, one concern I seriously
have is your heat treat,

14:35.959 --> 14:37.584
with a minute left.

14:37.627 --> 14:41.254
I assumed that less
than a minute would be enough

14:41.298 --> 14:42.922
to heat the very edge,

14:42.966 --> 14:45.341
because of the powerful forges
that we have here.

14:45.385 --> 14:48.219
That's a good plan,
especially for a chopping tool.

14:48.263 --> 14:50.388
You know, having the soft back
and the hard edge.

14:50.432 --> 14:51.389
Thank you.

14:51.433 --> 14:52.599
But, in that time,

14:52.642 --> 14:53.850
do you think you got it up
to about

14:53.894 --> 14:54.934
the 1,500 degree range
it needed?

14:54.978 --> 14:57.061
- I believe so, sir.
- Okay.

14:57.105 --> 14:58.730
Looking forward
to putting this to the test.

14:58.773 --> 15:00.064
Thank you.

15:00.108 --> 15:01.232
(Doug)
That is a nice design.

15:01.276 --> 15:03.484
I like the feel of it.

15:03.528 --> 15:06.237
You know, I'm quite familiar
with the panday--

15:06.281 --> 15:09.324
another term for bladesmith,
from the old ways.

15:09.367 --> 15:11.409
The thing that worried me
for a second there

15:11.453 --> 15:13.745
was when
you had to leave the forge.

15:13.788 --> 15:15.079
I thought you quit on us,

15:15.123 --> 15:17.123
but I was glad to see
you come back.

15:17.167 --> 15:18.917
And despite everything
that happened,

15:18.960 --> 15:21.127
you were still able
to forge this weapon.

15:21.171 --> 15:22.754
Thank you.

15:22.797 --> 15:24.172
(Wil)
Jonathan,

15:24.215 --> 15:26.049
please present your weapon
to the judges.

15:30.847 --> 15:33.097
Yeah, there are some issues
with this, definitely.

15:33.141 --> 15:34.265
Absolutely.

15:34.309 --> 15:35.350
You know,
where offset fullers

15:35.393 --> 15:36.309
and everything else.

15:36.353 --> 15:37.769
(Jonathan)
Yes, sir.

15:37.812 --> 15:39.020
(Dave)
There's quite a bit to be done

15:39.064 --> 15:40.939
with this,
but, at the same time,

15:40.982 --> 15:44.150
you pulled that out
in record time,

15:44.194 --> 15:47.820
and it was really impressive
to watch you move that fast.

15:47.864 --> 15:49.030
Thank you, sir.

15:49.074 --> 15:50.782
I like the shape, Jonathan.

15:50.825 --> 15:52.450
Still needs some work.

15:52.494 --> 15:54.035
It's got a little wiggle in it,

15:54.079 --> 15:56.287
but excellent job.

15:56.331 --> 15:57.830
Thank you.

15:57.874 --> 16:00.625
James, please present
your weapon to the judges.

16:00.669 --> 16:02.961
♪ ♪

16:03.004 --> 16:04.754
(J.)
We've all broken blades,

16:04.798 --> 16:07.090
but I've got to tell you,
fantastic effort.

16:07.133 --> 16:08.466
(James)
Man, it's--

16:08.510 --> 16:10.969
I mean you grabbed
another piece of steel,

16:11.012 --> 16:13.471
and you went to town.

16:13.515 --> 16:15.473
I was actually looking forward
to seeing that shape

16:15.517 --> 16:16.432
you were working on too.

16:16.476 --> 16:18.476
It had big sweep to it.

16:18.520 --> 16:20.812
You know, if it hadn't
have broke on the anvil--

16:20.855 --> 16:23.022
But unfortunately,
the blade you're handing us

16:23.066 --> 16:26.484
isn't quenched,
and therefore, can't be a blade.

16:26.528 --> 16:27.694
(James)
Yes, sir.

16:27.737 --> 16:29.028
(Wil)
James,

16:29.072 --> 16:30.363
I'd like to say one more thing.

16:30.407 --> 16:31.698
There's metal,

16:31.741 --> 16:32.740
and then there's mettle.

16:32.784 --> 16:34.075
Yes.

16:34.119 --> 16:35.493
And you've shown us
your mettle.

16:35.537 --> 16:37.370
- Please, surrender your weapon.
- Yes, sir.

16:37.414 --> 16:38.830
(James)
All I can say is, I made errors

16:38.873 --> 16:42.166
to try to give myself more time,

16:42.210 --> 16:44.002
and it backfired on me.

16:44.045 --> 16:46.629
I did Texas proud
for being who I am,

16:46.673 --> 16:48.631
not for the way
that I performed in there.

16:48.675 --> 16:52.176
♪ ♪

16:52.220 --> 16:53.344
(Wil)
Gentlemen,

16:53.388 --> 16:55.847
this is round two.

16:55.890 --> 16:58.182
Your second challenge
is to turn your blades

16:58.226 --> 17:01.185
into fully-functioning,
operational weapons.

17:01.229 --> 17:05.189
You must design and affix
a handle to your blade

17:05.233 --> 17:08.192
using the range of materials
provided for you.

17:08.236 --> 17:10.361
You will have just three hours.

17:10.405 --> 17:14.032
You can use that time to address
any problems or issues

17:14.075 --> 17:16.075
that you had from round one.

17:16.119 --> 17:17.869
When the time runs out,

17:17.912 --> 17:20.788
your weapons' strength
and durability will be tested

17:20.832 --> 17:22.081
in a coconut chop,

17:22.125 --> 17:24.417
as well as its ability
to hold an edge

17:24.461 --> 17:27.378
in a specially designed
sharpness test.

17:27.422 --> 17:28.921
After this challenge,

17:28.965 --> 17:33.217
only two of you will advance
to the final round.

17:33.261 --> 17:35.428
Your time starts...

17:35.472 --> 17:36.471
Now.

17:36.514 --> 17:38.598
♪ ♪

17:38.641 --> 17:41.059
(Jonathan)
Had I have finished the first
blade without cracking it,

17:41.102 --> 17:44.228
three hours would be a cakewalk.

17:44.272 --> 17:48.900
But I have so much catch-up
to do that I am just terrified

17:48.943 --> 17:51.986
that my time management is gonna
become the biggest issue.

17:52.030 --> 17:53.029
[metal clanging]

17:53.073 --> 17:54.781
Oh, God.

17:54.824 --> 17:57.909
My first thing to tackle is
to assess the fullering issue.

17:57.952 --> 17:59.285
♪ ♪

17:59.329 --> 18:01.537
He's slowed that grinder
down quite a bit.

18:01.581 --> 18:03.081
Well, he's trying
to clean up his fuller.

18:03.124 --> 18:04.582
(Wil)
Okay.

18:04.626 --> 18:06.709
The fullers,
they are the thing that I hate.

18:06.753 --> 18:10.588
And I'm having a really
hard time lining these up.

18:10.632 --> 18:11.798
(J.)
He does not look happy

18:11.841 --> 18:13.382
with his second blade.

18:13.426 --> 18:15.218
And I hope that doesn't sit
like a cloud

18:15.261 --> 18:19.430
hanging over him
during the second challenge.

18:19.474 --> 18:21.766
(Phil)
First thing is to try to fix
my fuller,

18:21.810 --> 18:23.142
and make it the right length,

18:23.186 --> 18:25.603
and get it cleaned up
as much as I can.

18:25.647 --> 18:27.105
(J.)
I like what Phil's doing.

18:27.148 --> 18:30.108
Phil's got a dremel bit
in the drill press,

18:30.151 --> 18:33.152
using the vice as a guide
to clean up his fuller.

18:33.196 --> 18:35.655
- Oh, okay.
- That's clever.

18:35.698 --> 18:37.949
(Phil)
I'm a fifth generation
craftsman,

18:37.992 --> 18:39.659
and there's a lot of projects

18:39.702 --> 18:41.953
that have had to be done
in timely manners,

18:41.996 --> 18:45.081
and we just do what it takes
to get it done.

18:45.125 --> 18:47.083
♪ ♪

18:47.127 --> 18:49.127
(Ryu)
My strategy for this round

18:49.170 --> 18:53.297
is sharpen the knife
and finish the file work.

18:53.341 --> 18:55.842
Then put a very simple
but a functional

18:55.885 --> 18:57.510
handle on the blade.

18:57.554 --> 18:59.262
(Wil)
It's like a man-powered
belt grinder.

18:59.305 --> 19:01.139
There you go,
that's exactly what it is.

19:01.182 --> 19:03.307
We've got all the modern
versions of the tools

19:03.351 --> 19:04.892
that he's making.

19:04.936 --> 19:06.477
(J.)
And he wants the primitive
versions.

19:06.521 --> 19:07.854
(Wil)
And he wants
the primitive versions.

19:07.897 --> 19:10.148
How does that affect
his time, overall?

19:10.191 --> 19:13.401
(Dave)
It's gonna kill him.

19:13.444 --> 19:14.652
(Jonathan)
In my head,

19:14.696 --> 19:16.320
I already had
kind of a color palette.

19:16.364 --> 19:18.156
Which,
I know I want to use copper.

19:18.199 --> 19:19.782
Because I'm gonna use
the copper,

19:19.826 --> 19:23.661
I try and find a really neutral,
highly-figured burl wood

19:23.705 --> 19:25.496
for the bulk of the handle.

19:25.540 --> 19:27.498
- Almost an hour.
- You all right?

19:27.542 --> 19:28.666
Yeah.

19:28.710 --> 19:30.168
(Jonathan)
At this point,

19:30.211 --> 19:32.295
I need to get that bolster
on the tang.

19:32.338 --> 19:34.714
I have 45 minutes left.

19:34.757 --> 19:36.215
It's enough time
to get everything done,

19:36.259 --> 19:38.634
but I cannot have
anything else go wrong.

19:38.678 --> 19:42.013
♪ ♪

19:42.056 --> 19:43.055
- There we go.
- Dang.

19:43.099 --> 19:44.682
[bleep].

19:44.726 --> 19:47.602
[heavy rock chord]

19:51.524 --> 19:53.691
[heavy rock chord]

19:53.735 --> 19:58.654
♪ ♪

19:58.698 --> 19:59.739
- Dang it.
- There we go.

19:59.782 --> 20:01.532
That's what I was worried about.

20:01.576 --> 20:02.992
(Jonathan)
I'm thinking too much,

20:03.036 --> 20:04.410
and I'm not paying
enough attention,

20:04.454 --> 20:06.746
and I pressed too hard
on that bolster

20:06.789 --> 20:07.955
and it snaps in half.

20:07.999 --> 20:09.832
Jonathan can definitely
pull this out.

20:09.876 --> 20:12.251
He just needs to make sure
he doesn't get frustrated.

20:12.295 --> 20:15.254
I don't have enough time
to do what I want to do.

20:15.298 --> 20:17.089
I'm gonna take this
as a failure,

20:17.133 --> 20:19.592
and I'm gonna make the handle
as good as I can make it.

20:19.636 --> 20:22.428
Come on baby, come on baby,
come on baby, come on.

20:22.472 --> 20:23.930
Another 1/8 inch,
come on.

20:23.973 --> 20:25.431
(Wil)
One hour.

20:25.475 --> 20:28.434
You have one hour
to complete your work.

20:28.478 --> 20:31.437
♪ ♪

20:31.481 --> 20:33.439
(Phil)
The epoxy hasn't set up
in the pins,

20:33.483 --> 20:35.566
so they're not holding it solid.

20:35.610 --> 20:37.485
So now,
I have to go to the anvil

20:37.528 --> 20:38.861
and peen 'em on both sides

20:38.905 --> 20:40.780
so it'll hold
the handle material

20:40.823 --> 20:43.282
to the tang and the blade.

20:43.326 --> 20:47.119
The warp on this blade is
a little worse than I thought,

20:47.163 --> 20:49.538
but I don't want to risk
trying to straighten it

20:49.582 --> 20:51.082
and cracking the blade.

20:51.125 --> 20:53.501
So I'm gonna grind it
the way that it is,

20:53.544 --> 20:55.378
and finish it out
with the warp in.

20:55.421 --> 20:58.005
♪ ♪

20:58.049 --> 21:01.384
I'm the type of guy who doesn't
overthink anything, really.

21:01.427 --> 21:04.136
So when it comes to
choosing handle,

21:04.180 --> 21:05.972
I'm just gonna pick
the colors I like.

21:06.015 --> 21:07.890
(Dave)
Now, I understand the fact that

21:07.934 --> 21:11.018
it's great watching someone do
hand work and everything else,

21:11.062 --> 21:13.688
but in a three-hour challenge,

21:13.731 --> 21:16.649
you know, sometimes you got
to cut to the chase.

21:16.693 --> 21:18.401
I like to do it all by hand,

21:18.444 --> 21:21.612
but here's something
the judges don't know about me.

21:21.656 --> 21:24.615
I'm actually really bad-ass
with an angle grinder.

21:24.659 --> 21:26.367
♪ ♪

21:26.411 --> 21:27.952
(Wil)
Oh, my God.

21:27.996 --> 21:30.705
It looks like somebody threw
a hand grenade

21:30.748 --> 21:32.915
into a flour factory over there.

21:32.959 --> 21:38.170
♪ ♪

21:38.214 --> 21:40.673
It's just another day
at the office.

21:40.717 --> 21:42.758
(Wil)
Ten, nine,

21:42.802 --> 21:44.719
eight, seven,

21:44.762 --> 21:46.679
six, five,

21:46.723 --> 21:48.681
four, three,

21:48.725 --> 21:50.725
two, one.

21:50.768 --> 21:54.228
Your time is up.

21:54.272 --> 21:55.896
(Ryu)
I look at the other guys' blade,

21:55.940 --> 21:58.649
and they look pretty ordinary,

21:58.693 --> 22:00.026
and mine doesn't.

22:00.069 --> 22:03.237
So I think that gives me
a little bit of an edge.

22:03.281 --> 22:04.989
(Jonathan)
I feel very good
about the blade.

22:05.033 --> 22:07.033
As far as the strength
and the durability,

22:07.076 --> 22:08.701
I think it'll do fine.

22:08.745 --> 22:11.370
Maybe somebody has a failure.
Maybe it's me.

22:11.414 --> 22:13.873
But that would definitely
be something

22:13.916 --> 22:17.293
that I wouldn't see coming.

22:17.337 --> 22:18.878
♪ ♪

22:18.921 --> 22:20.546
(Wil)
Gentlemen,

22:20.590 --> 22:23.049
this is the weapons test.

22:23.092 --> 22:26.177
First, J. is gonna test
your weapons' strength

22:26.220 --> 22:28.846
and durability
in a coconut chop.

22:28.890 --> 22:31.640
J.?

22:31.684 --> 22:33.267
(J.)
Bladesmiths,

22:33.311 --> 22:35.603
this is gonna test
the heat-treated edges

22:35.646 --> 22:37.063
of your blades

22:37.106 --> 22:38.189
and see how well
they hold up

22:38.232 --> 22:40.232
against these tough,
fibrous shells.

22:40.276 --> 22:42.943
I'm gonna do one chop
per coconut,

22:42.987 --> 22:45.154
three coconuts per blade.

22:45.198 --> 22:46.989
After each one,
I'm gonna check,

22:47.033 --> 22:48.741
see any chipping,
warping,

22:48.785 --> 22:50.409
any issues.

22:50.453 --> 22:52.411
Phil, you're up first.
Are you ready?

22:52.455 --> 22:53.412
Yes, sir.

22:53.456 --> 22:54.789
(J.)
Let's do it.

22:54.832 --> 22:56.540
(Phil)
I'm feeling a little nervous.

22:56.584 --> 22:58.250
I think I'm sweating more now
than I did

22:58.294 --> 22:59.752
during the forging part
of the competition.

22:59.796 --> 23:03.089
♪ ♪

23:03.132 --> 23:04.757
(Phil)
J. cut the first coconut,

23:04.801 --> 23:06.467
and it just kind of
slid off the table

23:06.511 --> 23:07.927
and didn't cut right through it.

23:07.970 --> 23:10.012
♪ ♪

23:13.267 --> 23:14.433
[metal clatters]

23:14.477 --> 23:16.644
Oh, my gosh.

23:16.687 --> 23:18.813
(Phil)
Son of a bitch.

23:18.856 --> 23:20.439
I couldn't believe
that it broke off like that.

23:20.483 --> 23:22.274
I thought it would really
chop through the coconut

23:22.318 --> 23:23.776
with no problem.

23:23.820 --> 23:25.277
And now I'm in a situation
where I think

23:25.321 --> 23:26.862
the only way I can move on

23:26.906 --> 23:29.240
is if one of the other guys'
blades break.

23:29.283 --> 23:32.243
Well, Phil, I got to say,
it felt really good in hand.

23:32.286 --> 23:34.954
I wish it had
a little more weight to it.

23:34.997 --> 23:37.790
But, unfortunately,
it broke.

23:37.834 --> 23:39.458
So I'm not gonna
be able to continue

23:39.502 --> 23:40.459
with the sharpness test.

23:40.503 --> 23:43.295
Yeah.

23:43.339 --> 23:44.630
Ryu,
you're up next.

23:46.092 --> 23:47.466
(Ryu)
I'm not nervous right now.

23:47.510 --> 23:48.968
I'm actually pretty excited

23:49.011 --> 23:50.636
that they're gonna put my blade
to the test.

23:50.680 --> 23:51.929
I want to see what happens.

23:51.973 --> 23:59.895
♪ ♪

24:05.153 --> 24:06.318
Nice.

24:08.906 --> 24:10.489
All right, Ryu,
congratulations.

24:10.533 --> 24:13.451
You went through the coconuts.

24:13.494 --> 24:15.619
Concerns about your heat treat,
though.

24:15.663 --> 24:17.496
What used to be
a straight blade

24:17.540 --> 24:21.000
is no longer straight.

24:21.043 --> 24:22.543
Jonathan,

24:22.587 --> 24:24.879
you ready to put your weapon
up against the coconuts?

24:24.922 --> 24:25.921
(J.)
We're gonna do it anyway.

24:25.965 --> 24:27.339
I know.

24:27.383 --> 24:28.799
(Jonathan)
I'm certain that my knife

24:28.843 --> 24:31.677
is about to shatter
into a million pieces.

24:31.721 --> 24:35.181
It's just not built
to chop through coconuts.

24:35.224 --> 24:37.391
♪ ♪

24:44.775 --> 24:47.401
[heavy rock chord]

24:47.445 --> 24:49.069
(Jonathan)
I don't know

24:49.113 --> 24:50.905
if my knife's gonna hold up
to those coconuts,

24:50.948 --> 24:54.909
'cause they really do look
pretty ominous sitting up there.

24:54.952 --> 25:03.292
♪ ♪

25:03.336 --> 25:05.544
[speaks indistinctly]

25:05.588 --> 25:09.673
♪ ♪

25:09.717 --> 25:11.217
[sighs]

25:13.846 --> 25:16.764
Feeling better now,
Jonathan?

25:16.807 --> 25:18.641
(Jonathan)
Your edge held up well.

25:18.684 --> 25:20.100
No warping.

25:20.144 --> 25:22.436
Boxy handle, though.

25:22.480 --> 25:23.979
It's a little hard to control.

25:24.023 --> 25:26.190
But overall, good job.

25:26.234 --> 25:29.610
Gonna pass it off to Doug now
for the sharpness test.

25:29.654 --> 25:32.780
♪ ♪

25:32.823 --> 25:34.823
Okay, Ryu,
what I'm gonna do now is,

25:34.867 --> 25:36.450
I'm just gonna see
if it's held its edge.

25:36.494 --> 25:37.743
What I'm gonna do is,

25:37.787 --> 25:39.995
I'm just gonna do
a horizontal cut.

25:40.039 --> 25:42.289
I won't depend on power.

25:42.333 --> 25:43.457
I'm just gonna walk through.

25:43.501 --> 25:47.962
♪ ♪

25:54.220 --> 25:55.803
[speaks indistinctly]

25:55.846 --> 25:58.639
I think it cuts.

25:58.683 --> 26:00.474
- Good job.
- Thank you.

26:00.518 --> 26:01.684
(Ryu)
I'm pretty happy with the way

26:01.727 --> 26:03.394
my blade performed.

26:03.437 --> 26:05.688
It bent, instead of break.

26:05.731 --> 26:07.189
So that's a good thing.

26:07.233 --> 26:08.315
Okay, Jonathan.

26:08.359 --> 26:10.401
Let's see if it held its edge.

26:10.444 --> 26:14.530
♪ ♪

26:19.870 --> 26:22.830
Like hot iron through butter.

26:22.873 --> 26:24.832
Very good.

26:24.875 --> 26:26.417
There's a slight bit of comfort

26:26.460 --> 26:28.752
knowing that someone
had a complete failure,

26:28.796 --> 26:31.380
but what I turned in
is not something

26:31.424 --> 26:35.092
to just go in front of them
and expect praise about.

26:36.178 --> 26:39.138
[dramatic music]

26:39.181 --> 26:40.556
♪ ♪

26:40.600 --> 26:42.182
(Wil)
Gentlemen,

26:42.226 --> 26:43.934
the judges have come
to a decision.

26:43.978 --> 26:46.604
♪ ♪

26:46.647 --> 26:47.605
Phil,

26:47.648 --> 26:49.690
you did not make the cut.

26:49.734 --> 26:50.899
(J.)
I really liked

26:50.943 --> 26:52.776
where you were going
with the blade,

26:52.820 --> 26:55.404
and your edge actually held up
well during the coconut chop.

26:55.448 --> 26:58.616
But obviously, there was
an issue with your heat treat,

26:58.659 --> 27:00.701
and you had the tip fly off.

27:00.745 --> 27:03.203
Because of that,
we can't let you continue.

27:03.247 --> 27:05.289
I understand.

27:05.333 --> 27:08.626
Phil, please surrender
your weapon.

27:08.669 --> 27:10.294
I'm disappointed in myself.

27:10.338 --> 27:12.379
Thank you, gentlemen.
I appreciate the opportunity.

27:12.423 --> 27:15.716
(Phil)
I obviously agree
with the decision,

27:15.760 --> 27:17.468
but yeah, I was looking forward
to moving on.

27:17.511 --> 27:19.887
I really saw myself
in the finals.

27:19.930 --> 27:25.434
♪ ♪

27:25.478 --> 27:27.895
(Wil)
Ryu, Jonathan,

27:27.938 --> 27:31.023
you made it through
to the final round.

27:31.067 --> 27:32.608
So far,

27:32.652 --> 27:34.818
you've designed
and presented

27:34.862 --> 27:37.571
a weapon
in your own styles.

27:37.615 --> 27:40.157
Now we're gonna send you back
to your home forges

27:40.201 --> 27:42.534
where you will make one of the
most iconic weapons

27:42.578 --> 27:46.747
from history--

27:46.791 --> 27:49.583
the Viking battle axe.

27:49.627 --> 27:52.002
The Viking battle axe
was a brutal killing weapon

27:52.046 --> 27:54.463
that played a significant role
throughout history.

27:54.507 --> 27:56.423
Viking warriors
were mostly farmers,

27:56.467 --> 27:57.966
so when going off to fight,

27:58.010 --> 27:59.677
they would pick the tool
they had close at hand,

27:59.720 --> 28:02.054
which was often
a woodcutting axe.

28:02.098 --> 28:03.931
When later models
took on shapes

28:03.974 --> 28:05.599
more convenient
to the fighting man,

28:05.643 --> 28:07.267
the battle axe was born.

28:07.311 --> 28:08.769
The haft was made of wood,

28:08.813 --> 28:10.938
and the curved head
allowed the axe to be used

28:10.981 --> 28:12.356
to hook an opponent's ankle,

28:12.400 --> 28:14.358
throwing him off balance
and onto the ground--

28:14.402 --> 28:16.777
positioning the Viking
to go in for the kill

28:16.821 --> 28:19.488
with the large,
razor-sharp cutting edge.

28:19.532 --> 28:22.449
The battle axe has a long
and colorful association

28:22.493 --> 28:24.034
with fantasy film
and literature,

28:24.078 --> 28:25.619
being the weapon of choice
for the dwarves

28:25.663 --> 28:27.287
in<i> The Lord of the Rings</i>
and<i> The Hobbit,</i>

28:27.331 --> 28:29.957
as well as for the players
of fantasy computer games

28:30.000 --> 28:32.292
such as<i> World of Warcraft.</i>

28:32.336 --> 28:34.461
(Wil)
It must be a working,

28:34.505 --> 28:39.341
fully functional version
of that lethal weapon.

28:39.385 --> 28:42.553
You will have five days
to complete this challenge.

28:42.596 --> 28:44.596
(Jonathan)
I love making axes.

28:44.640 --> 28:48.225
It's so fun
to take a giant block of metal

28:48.269 --> 28:50.811
and move it so many
different directions.

28:50.855 --> 28:52.146
(Ryu)
I've come this far

28:52.189 --> 28:54.148
with only my skills
and my hands,

28:54.191 --> 28:56.024
and even though
I don't have the proper tools

28:56.068 --> 28:58.068
to produce a Viking axe,

28:58.112 --> 29:00.446
I'm going to come back
with a bad-ass one.

29:00.489 --> 29:01.864
After five days,

29:01.907 --> 29:04.700
you will present
your battle axes to the judges,

29:04.744 --> 29:06.160
where they will put them through

29:06.203 --> 29:09.538
a series of rigorous
and dynamic tests.

29:09.582 --> 29:11.665
Once those tests are completed,

29:11.709 --> 29:16.336
one of you will walk out of here
with a check for $10,000--

29:16.380 --> 29:20.382
and the title
of<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

29:20.426 --> 29:23.218
(Wil)
Good luck, gentlemen.

29:23.262 --> 29:26.221
[industrial rock music]

29:26.265 --> 29:27.681
♪ ♪

29:27.725 --> 29:29.183
(Jonathan)
I'm back at the Dog House,

29:29.226 --> 29:31.018
and it feels
a lot more comfortable here

29:31.061 --> 29:32.895
than it did
in the first two rounds.

29:32.938 --> 29:36.732
I'm doing a multiple layer,
patterned steel battle axe.

29:36.776 --> 29:40.068
The Vikings, they used a lot
of multi-layered steel.

29:40.112 --> 29:42.488
Overall, this will be
one sturdy axe.

29:42.531 --> 29:44.072
♪ ♪

29:44.116 --> 29:46.700
I am super pumped
about this battle axe.

29:46.744 --> 29:50.621
I just feel like the judges
never saw what I can do.

29:50.664 --> 29:53.540
They just saw how well
I can save my butt.

29:53.584 --> 29:56.418
So I'm going to hand them
the absolute best thing

29:56.462 --> 29:58.253
I have ever made
in my entire life.

29:58.297 --> 30:06.220
♪ ♪

30:07.807 --> 30:09.932
(Ryu)
The studio shop
had everything, man.

30:09.975 --> 30:12.100
I got the bare bones.

30:12.144 --> 30:14.102
Only the basics.

30:14.146 --> 30:17.147
My forge is basically
a cast-iron pot

30:17.191 --> 30:19.900
with a hole
drilled in the bottom,

30:19.944 --> 30:22.069
where I attached a black pipe.

30:22.112 --> 30:24.905
And on that black pipe,
I attached a hair dryer.

30:24.949 --> 30:28.909
Using the hair dryer,
I introduce more oxygen.

30:28.953 --> 30:30.577
And the more oxygen
you put in,

30:30.621 --> 30:32.371
the hotter it gets.

30:34.792 --> 30:36.667
I've made smaller axes before,

30:36.710 --> 30:39.419
but I've never made an axe
this big.

30:39.463 --> 30:41.255
I'm gonna stretch out the metal,

30:41.298 --> 30:43.757
and I'm gonna wrap
it around a pipe

30:43.801 --> 30:47.761
to make an eye for the handle.

30:47.805 --> 30:49.638
I really have no heat,

30:49.682 --> 30:53.100
because it's so big
it doesn't fit in my forge.

30:53.143 --> 30:55.686
I had to make some adjustments
to remedy that.

30:55.729 --> 30:58.772
When you're working
with high powered power tools,

30:58.816 --> 31:01.817
you got to remember--
safety first.

31:01.861 --> 31:04.319
You got to wear
some eye protection,

31:04.363 --> 31:06.321
and respirator.

31:06.365 --> 31:09.283
♪ ♪

31:09.326 --> 31:10.617
The way it's going right now,

31:10.661 --> 31:12.619
I'm not getting enough heat.

31:12.663 --> 31:14.955
I'm losing a lot of heat
very quickly.

31:14.999 --> 31:16.498
So I might start over.

31:16.542 --> 31:18.125
Or make a new forge.

31:18.168 --> 31:20.294
♪ ♪

31:20.337 --> 31:23.005
(Jonathan)
The competition is definitely
affecting me.

31:23.048 --> 31:24.298
I don't know why
I don't just come in here

31:24.341 --> 31:25.883
and forge like I always do,

31:25.926 --> 31:28.176
but this contest sort of
just messes me up.

31:28.220 --> 31:30.345
Man!

31:30.389 --> 31:32.347
I just wasn't paying attention.

31:32.391 --> 31:34.474
I took my eye off it,
and I cooked it.

31:34.518 --> 31:35.642
It's done.

31:35.686 --> 31:37.311
I got to start over.

31:37.354 --> 31:40.272
Unbelievable!

31:40.316 --> 31:42.983
♪ ♪

31:43.027 --> 31:45.152
(Ryu)
The first forge wasn't working

31:45.195 --> 31:46.695
because it was too small.

31:46.739 --> 31:49.656
So I added a satellite dish
around it.

31:49.700 --> 31:52.534
So I'll be able
to add more coal,

31:52.578 --> 31:54.161
and make a bigger fire.

31:54.204 --> 31:57.915
♪ ♪

31:57.958 --> 31:59.666
Looking good right now.

31:59.710 --> 32:01.335
I can move onto the fun part.

32:01.378 --> 32:03.629
[siren blaring]

32:03.672 --> 32:04.671
(man)
What is this?

32:08.093 --> 32:09.718
The firefighters came,

32:09.762 --> 32:13.138
and unfortunately,
I was delayed an hour.

32:13.182 --> 32:15.015
Your biggest thing
that we got to deal with

32:15.059 --> 32:16.725
is the fact that you're...

32:17.937 --> 32:19.519
(Ryu)
I have to move the forge

32:19.563 --> 32:21.355
and reposition everything.

32:21.398 --> 32:24.066
Hopefully it doesn't affect me
too much towards the end.

32:24.109 --> 32:25.525
- Thank you, sir.
- Good luck to you.

32:25.569 --> 32:26.485
Appreciate it.

32:26.528 --> 32:27.527
I really wish you good luck,

32:27.571 --> 32:29.363
and I hope you win.

32:29.406 --> 32:32.032
(Jonathan)
I forged another axe head,

32:32.076 --> 32:34.785
and this time,
the blade held together.

32:34.828 --> 32:37.245
I think the judges are gonna
be impressed

32:37.289 --> 32:39.206
with the axe in general.

32:39.249 --> 32:41.917
We're buttoned up with
a really nice, top-notch handle

32:41.961 --> 32:43.710
with leather wraps
that go along with the head

32:43.754 --> 32:45.754
that we've worked so hard for.

32:45.798 --> 32:48.215
It's an end result
that I think looks good

32:48.258 --> 32:49.216
and I'm proud of.

32:49.259 --> 32:51.301
So no matter what they think,

32:51.345 --> 32:54.012
I'm proud of what I'm gonna put
in front of them this round.

32:54.056 --> 32:58.100
♪ ♪

32:58.143 --> 32:59.101
(Ryu)
Last night,

32:59.144 --> 33:00.936
I finished the blade.

33:00.980 --> 33:03.855
And now, we're gonna
start working on the handle.

33:03.899 --> 33:05.732
I don't have electric saw,

33:05.776 --> 33:09.361
so I'm gonna
have to carve this down.

33:09.405 --> 33:15.409
♪ ♪

33:15.452 --> 33:19.830
I spent the last hour
pounding in the handle

33:19.873 --> 33:22.207
at the same time making it.

33:22.251 --> 33:23.417
It was tough,

33:23.460 --> 33:25.252
but I'm just really curious

33:25.295 --> 33:27.087
what the judges
are gonna say, really.

33:27.131 --> 33:29.589
A battle axe doesn't have
to be smooth and shiny.

33:29.633 --> 33:31.091
It just has to work.

33:31.135 --> 33:34.428
It doesn't have
to be pretty to split skulls.

33:34.471 --> 33:37.431
[heavy rock chord]

33:40.853 --> 33:43.020
[heavy rock chord]

33:43.063 --> 33:45.397
♪ ♪

33:45.441 --> 33:46.398
(Wil)
Gentlemen,

33:46.442 --> 33:48.734
welcome back to the forge.

33:48.777 --> 33:53.113
I hope that your five days
at home were very productive.

33:53.157 --> 33:55.407
Jonathan,
how did it go for you?

33:55.451 --> 33:59.369
It was a lot bumpier
than I envisioned.

33:59.413 --> 34:03.123
I really like the undercut
and the contours in it.

34:03.167 --> 34:05.292
Not only did I build you
a battle axe,

34:05.335 --> 34:06.752
I made my own metal,

34:06.795 --> 34:08.962
and then made an axe
from that metal.

34:09.006 --> 34:12.299
I feel like it's a $10,000
weapon, that's for sure.

34:12.342 --> 34:14.092
How'd it go, Ryu?

34:14.136 --> 34:16.011
It was a bit
of a challenge.

34:16.055 --> 34:17.763
(Ryu)
I left the whole piece raw,

34:17.806 --> 34:19.431
and rough.

34:19.475 --> 34:22.684
That says a lot about me
and how I make my blades.

34:22.728 --> 34:24.269
It's hand-forged,

34:24.313 --> 34:26.480
and I want it to look
like it's hand-forged.

34:26.523 --> 34:28.815
I don't want to clean it up
and mirror polish it.

34:28.859 --> 34:30.984
Especially
it's a Viking axe.

34:31.028 --> 34:33.779
I don't think Vikings cared
for a mirror polish back then.

34:33.822 --> 34:37.199
They're not a bunch
of pretty boys.

34:37.242 --> 34:39.618
Well, the $10,000

34:39.661 --> 34:41.995
and the title of<i> Forged in Fire</i>
champion are so close,

34:42.039 --> 34:44.122
you can probably taste it.

34:44.166 --> 34:48.293
But each of your blades will
have to endure three trials.

34:48.337 --> 34:50.962
There will be a kill test,
a chop test,

34:51.006 --> 34:53.423
and a strength test.

34:53.467 --> 34:56.635
First is the kill test.

34:56.678 --> 34:58.011
Doug?

35:01.100 --> 35:02.808
To test the lethality
of your axe,

35:02.851 --> 35:04.643
I will strike the side
of the beef here,

35:04.686 --> 35:07.437
and see what kind of damage
it does.

35:07.481 --> 35:08.855
Jonathan,
you're up first.

35:08.899 --> 35:10.148
I'm ready.

35:10.192 --> 35:11.817
I'm looking at the rack of meat,

35:11.860 --> 35:15.695
and I'm not sure if the axe
is gonna hold up.

35:15.739 --> 35:17.823
Let's try it.

35:17.866 --> 35:20.867
[heavy rock music]

35:20.911 --> 35:27.290
♪ ♪

35:33.590 --> 35:36.049
Your edge held.

35:36.093 --> 35:39.719
(Doug)
It crushed through three bones.

35:39.763 --> 35:41.221
It will kill.

35:41.265 --> 35:43.014
Yes, it will.

35:43.058 --> 35:44.015
(Doug)
For the next test,

35:44.059 --> 35:45.392
I'm gonna pass it over

35:45.435 --> 35:48.645
to our European
historical weapons expert.

35:48.689 --> 35:49.855
Dave?

35:51.775 --> 35:53.525
Thanks, Doug.

35:53.569 --> 35:54.526
(Dave)
Gentlemen,

35:54.570 --> 35:56.361
the Viking axe was designed

35:56.405 --> 35:59.739
to create the maximum amount
of carnage on the battlefield.

35:59.783 --> 36:02.117
To test it,
in the chop test,

36:02.161 --> 36:03.493
I'm gonna take five blows

36:03.537 --> 36:06.121
against this hardened
panel of oak.

36:06.165 --> 36:09.374
Oak was the common building
material of the time,

36:09.418 --> 36:12.586
and this was the breaching tool
of the time.

36:12.629 --> 36:13.753
I'm ready.

36:13.797 --> 36:15.088
(Dave)
All right.

36:15.132 --> 36:23.054
♪ ♪

36:29.146 --> 36:30.562
I don't know if I can crawl
through that,

36:30.606 --> 36:33.565
but it seemed to do the job.

36:33.609 --> 36:35.275
That round handle, though.

36:35.319 --> 36:37.485
Boy, it wants to twist
in your hand.

36:37.529 --> 36:39.571
(Doug)
Bit of an issue.

36:39.615 --> 36:42.574
Overall,
it felt pretty good.

36:42.618 --> 36:43.825
(Doug)
Ryu, You're up next.

36:43.869 --> 36:45.118
Are you ready?

36:45.162 --> 36:47.245
I'm ready.
Let's do it.

36:47.289 --> 36:50.916
I'm hoping that the judges
will push my axe over the limit.

36:50.959 --> 36:54.586
I want them to throw everything
they got at that axe.

36:54.630 --> 36:57.589
(Ryu)
I don't think my axe can fail.

36:57.633 --> 37:00.592
[heavy rock music]

37:00.636 --> 37:06.890
♪ ♪

37:14.483 --> 37:15.899
(Doug)
The handle's a little slippery.

37:15.943 --> 37:18.109
So first couple of tries
it was slipping off,

37:18.153 --> 37:21.738
I had to make sure
it didn't go fly off my hand.

37:21.782 --> 37:25.700
You cut about three
and into the fourth bone.

37:27.162 --> 37:30.372
This, I believe,
is a killer.

37:30.415 --> 37:32.540
- Good job.
- Thank you very much.

37:32.584 --> 37:35.252
(Doug)
Dave?

37:35.295 --> 37:36.836
(Ryu)
My axe may not be pretty,

37:36.880 --> 37:39.798
but it can definitely
split some skulls.

37:39.841 --> 37:47.764
♪ ♪

37:50.811 --> 37:52.477
(Dave)
Well, felt pretty good.

37:52.521 --> 37:54.980
My hand could travel
on that handle.

37:55.023 --> 37:56.731
Whereas with that leather wrap,

37:56.775 --> 38:00.318
I couldn't really move my hand
while I was swinging.

38:00.362 --> 38:01.486
Nice job.

38:01.530 --> 38:02.988
Thank you.

38:03.031 --> 38:04.614
(Wil)
Well, gentlemen,

38:04.658 --> 38:06.366
your weapons have performed
well thus far.

38:06.410 --> 38:08.535
But it's not over yet.

38:08.578 --> 38:10.495
We're gonna see
just how much punishment

38:10.539 --> 38:14.457
your weapons can take
in our strength test.

38:14.501 --> 38:17.377
Doug?

38:17.421 --> 38:19.504
For the strength test,
your axes will be placed

38:19.548 --> 38:22.507
in a specially designed
impact device.

38:22.551 --> 38:25.302
The arm is set
to deliver maximum force

38:25.345 --> 38:26.845
at the point of impact.

38:26.888 --> 38:30.557
We will deliver three strikes
on the shield.

38:30.600 --> 38:32.350
That will give us
a good indication

38:32.394 --> 38:35.020
of how much pressure
your axe can take.

38:35.063 --> 38:38.064
Let's see if your weapon
will survive this test.

38:38.108 --> 38:41.192
(Doug)
Jonathan, let's test it.

38:41.236 --> 38:43.445
This is the only point
in the testing

38:43.488 --> 38:45.864
that I'm a little afraid
about how it's gonna hold up

38:45.907 --> 38:48.992
because that machine
looks really mean.

38:49.036 --> 38:50.035
(Doug)
Three,

38:50.078 --> 38:51.703
two, one.

38:51.747 --> 38:52.704
Engaging.

38:59.921 --> 39:02.380
[heavy rock chord]

39:02.424 --> 39:03.340
Jonathan,

39:03.383 --> 39:04.883
let's test it.

39:04.926 --> 39:06.718
Either the haft will break,

39:06.762 --> 39:09.971
or I'll get some sort of damage
to the edge of the blade.

39:10.015 --> 39:13.808
My axe wasn't built
to be run by a machine.

39:13.852 --> 39:15.101
(Doug)
Three,

39:15.145 --> 39:16.561
two, one

39:16.605 --> 39:17.520
Engaging.

39:17.564 --> 39:19.981
♪ ♪

39:20.025 --> 39:21.232
(Doug)
Engaging.

39:21.276 --> 39:23.735
♪ ♪

39:23.779 --> 39:24.986
Engaging.

39:25.030 --> 39:32.744
♪ ♪

39:32.788 --> 39:36.081
I don't see any clear
indentations on your edge.

39:36.124 --> 39:38.917
(Doug)
A little indentation
on the shield,

39:38.960 --> 39:41.586
and your haft
seems to have held.

39:41.630 --> 39:44.214
- Good job.
- Thank you.

39:44.257 --> 39:46.758
(Doug)
Ryu, you're next.

39:46.802 --> 39:47.926
(Doug)
Three,

39:47.969 --> 39:49.427
two, one.

39:49.471 --> 39:50.553
Engaging.

39:50.597 --> 39:53.890
♪ ♪

39:53.934 --> 39:56.935
When I saw the first strike,
I was just disappointed.

39:56.978 --> 39:58.978
I just wanted more power.

39:59.022 --> 40:02.774
♪ ♪

40:02.818 --> 40:03.900
(Doug)
Engaging.

40:03.944 --> 40:06.236
♪ ♪

40:14.162 --> 40:15.954
That split the shield in half,

40:15.997 --> 40:19.457
and all the way through.

40:19.501 --> 40:21.626
Edge held.

40:21.670 --> 40:23.711
Haft is still secure.

40:23.755 --> 40:26.172
- Good job.
- Thank you.

40:26.216 --> 40:29.467
I think this is gonna be
a tough decision for the judges,

40:29.511 --> 40:31.136
and that's what I want.

40:31.179 --> 40:34.264
I want it to be fair.

40:34.307 --> 40:37.267
[dramatic music]

40:37.310 --> 40:42.397
♪ ♪

40:42.441 --> 40:44.482
(Wil)
Ryu, Jonathan,

40:44.526 --> 40:46.192
you've had five days

40:46.236 --> 40:50.989
to create a Viking battle axe
of your own design,

40:51.032 --> 40:52.866
and you've both done
marvelous work.

40:52.909 --> 40:54.325
However,

40:54.369 --> 40:57.495
there can only be one champion.

40:57.539 --> 40:58.830
J.

40:58.874 --> 41:01.249
(J.)
Ryu, I really like the profile

41:01.293 --> 41:03.501
that your Viking axe
brought out.

41:03.545 --> 41:05.962
You know, the feeling it,
the look of it.

41:06.006 --> 41:08.006
I wish there was a little more
belly to the blade,

41:08.049 --> 41:09.757
but we also have
some symmetry issues.

41:09.801 --> 41:13.136
Where your blade coming off
the eye at a slight cant,

41:13.180 --> 41:16.598
and the blade edge along
the handle is a bit off also.

41:16.641 --> 41:19.517
So those are points
that concern me.

41:19.561 --> 41:20.852
(Wil)
Doug.

41:20.896 --> 41:22.395
The design of your battle axe

41:22.439 --> 41:26.441
really allowed me
to feel the blade in my hand.

41:26.485 --> 41:28.860
Good job.

41:28.904 --> 41:30.778
Jonathan, I like the pattern
welding you did.

41:30.822 --> 41:32.530
I mean,
that was a great touch.

41:32.574 --> 41:34.532
Your fit up on your haft
was great,

41:34.576 --> 41:36.618
and I loved the profile,

41:36.661 --> 41:39.704
but you kind of lost track
on the handle.

41:39.748 --> 41:41.748
The roundedness of your handle
does give it a tendency

41:41.791 --> 41:43.333
to move around too much,

41:43.376 --> 41:45.543
to where it doesn't feel like
you can tell

41:45.587 --> 41:49.339
where the edge of the blade is
at all times.

41:49.382 --> 41:52.884
(Wil)
You have both done yourselves
proud as bladesmiths.

41:52.928 --> 41:54.719
However,
in this competition,

41:54.763 --> 41:58.264
there can only be one winner.

41:58.308 --> 42:01.059
Ryu.

42:01.102 --> 42:03.102
You are the<i> Forged in Fire</i>
champion.

42:03.146 --> 42:05.647
(Wil)
Congratulations.

42:05.690 --> 42:06.606
Good job, buddy.

42:06.650 --> 42:08.066
Good job.

42:08.109 --> 42:09.734
(Wil)
Jonathan,

42:09.778 --> 42:13.154
your weapon
did not make the cut.

42:13.198 --> 42:15.740
There was some great aspects
to your blade,

42:15.784 --> 42:18.910
but a slaggy scale
on a blade,

42:18.954 --> 42:20.245
the sloppiness up top,

42:20.288 --> 42:21.287
and the biggest thing
that hurt you

42:21.331 --> 42:23.081
was that dowel handle.

42:23.124 --> 42:25.959
Even though you did a nice job
adding some pigskin to it,

42:26.002 --> 42:28.086
it just wasn't enough
to get over the fact

42:28.129 --> 42:31.089
that that blade wanted to swing
around in people's hands.

42:31.132 --> 42:32.090
(Wil)
Jonathan,

42:32.133 --> 42:34.759
please surrender your weapon.

42:34.803 --> 42:35.885
(Jonathan)
I mean, I'm totally proud

42:35.929 --> 42:37.428
of the work that I'd done.

42:37.472 --> 42:39.097
I mean, I turned in a laminated
Viking battle axe.

42:39.140 --> 42:41.099
So I'm not--
[laughs]

42:41.142 --> 42:43.101
I'm not by any means going home
'cause I didn't do enough.

42:43.144 --> 42:47.188
In this case,
Ryu just did a better job.

42:47.232 --> 42:48.439
(Ryu)
I feel very proud right now.

42:48.483 --> 42:50.108
I worked really hard for this.

42:50.151 --> 42:51.609
I guess it paid off.

42:51.653 --> 42:54.487
The stress level got to you
in the first challenge.

42:54.531 --> 42:56.281
(J.)
You were able
to pull it together.

42:56.324 --> 42:57.615
I mean, you got a few issues,

42:57.659 --> 43:00.118
but you brought a true weapon

43:00.161 --> 43:01.286
you should definitely
be proud of.

43:01.329 --> 43:02.620
Thank you, sir.

43:02.664 --> 43:04.789
I put my soul into
forging that axe.

43:04.833 --> 43:06.791
I gave it everything I had.

43:06.835 --> 43:09.168
And now,
I walk out as a champion.
